<LP>
   A federal judge excoriated two lawyers who filed thousands
of asbestos-related claims, saying greed motivated them to
solicit and pursue many cases that apparently were
groundless.
   The two California lawyers, Gordon A. Stemple and Richard
F. Gerry, represented 6,000 asbestos claimants against
Raymark Industries Inc., an asbestos maker that paid $16
million to tire workers nationwide for injuries claimed by
Messrs. Stemple and Gerry. The company then sued the two
lawyers in 1987 challenging the validity of the claims and
alleging fraud and racketeering.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   In response to a pretrial motion seeking dismissal of the
suit, Judge Patrick F. Kelly, of Wichita, Kan., answered with
a scalding 63-page opinion. He accused the two lawyers -- and
three doctors they employed to evaluate the claims -- of
fraud, deceptive solicitation and "reckless disregard of the
truth."
   "It appears that this unusual, distasteful and
disappointing case emanates from the attorneys' greed, which
has clouded their professional judgment; i.e., their
indifference as to whether any of the 6,000 claims meet
professional standards or not," Judge Kelly wrote.
   Messrs. Stemple and Gerry formed the National Tire Workers
Litigation Project in 1986, equipped vans with X-ray machines
and traveled to Raymark tire plants across the country in the
"examobiles" to conduct massive employee examinations. In his
order, the judge called the technique an "unethical
nationwide solicitation process" and charged that the three
doctors involved compromised their professional
responsibility by using flawed screening procedures to churn
groundless claims.
   "There is evidence in this case which indicates that
{Messrs.} Stemple and Gerry violated ethical obligations by
conducting a contrived and deceptive solicitation program,"
the judge wrote.
   Reached at his office in Century City, Calif., Mr. Stemple
said he disagreed with the opinion and predicted that he, Mr.
Gerry and the three doctors will prevail when the case goes
before a jury. Mr. Gerry, of San Diego, was out of town and
couldn't be reached for comment.
   Raymark was a unit of Raytech Corp., a Bridgeport, Conn.,
maker of fastners and brake and clutch materials, that
stripped the company of its non-asbestos-related assets and
spun it off in 1988 to distance itself from asbestos
litigation. Raymark has been forced into bankruptcy-court
proceedings under the weight of more than 68,000
asbestos-related claims. Last year, Raytech sought
bankruptcy-court protection.
   The company has been known for particularly aggressive
litigation tactics, said Mr. Stemple, pointing to the suit
against him as the most recent example. But Raymark lawyer
William L. Myers Jr., of the Philadelphia firm of Ballard,
Spahr, Andrews &amp; Ingersoll, said Judge Kelly's opinion was a
"timely expression of judicial disapproval of mass-produced
lawsuits."
