   STUDENT-LOAN INQUIRY leads to indictment of ex-official at
Florida thrift.
   A federal grand jury in Tampa, Fla., returned a 25-count
indictment against Jeffrey A. Flatten, charging that he
conspired to defraud the U.S. Department of Education in
connection with its Guaranteed Student Loan Program. The
program makes low-interest loans available to students for
college expenses.
   Mr. Flatten, who headed Florida Federal Savings Bank's
student-loan division, was also charged with committing mail
fraud and stealing government funds.
   The indictment follows Florida Federal's conviction by the
federal jury for falsifying statements related to
government-backed student loans. Last month, in what is
believed to be the largest student-loan case ever prosecuted,
the federal jury found the company guilty of 43 counts of
falsifying statements between November 1986 and July 1987.
Two former officers were convicted of falsifying statements.
   In 1988, Florida Federal came under scrutiny for allegedly
filing as many as 17,000 fraudulent insurance claims on $35
million in student loans. The investigation helped spark a
management shake-up that resulted in the resignation of the
thrift's chairman.
   The indictment against Mr. Flatten alleges that from
November 1986 to September 1987 he conspired with other
officers and employees of Florida Federal to submit the
17,000 fraudulent claims. Those claims, the indictment says,
were supported by documents falsely reflecting that Florida
Federal performed required collection activity on the loans.
   In St. Petersburg, Fla., Florida Federal officials hadn't
any comment. Mr. Flatten couldn't be reached.
