   METROMEDIA WINS damages of $46 million in fraud suit.
   Metromedia Co. sued William D. Fugazy in 1987 for
allegedly fraudulently overstating the value of Fugazy
Express Inc., a limousine service that Metromedia acquired in
1985. Fugazy Express, which Metromedia owned for two years,
is in bankruptcy-law proceedings.
   In the civil-racketeering suit, Metromedia claimed Mr.
Fugazy overstated the value of the company by $7 million,
said Martin Shelton, an attorney for the Secaucus, N.J.,
communications company. Mr. Shelton said Metromedia,
controlled by billionaire John Kluge, had to invest an
additional $30 million in the company because of the alleged
misrepresentations.
   The jury hearing the case in federal court in Manhattan,
N.Y., awarded damages of $15 million, which Judge Robert
Carter trebled under racketeering law.
   Anthony Princi, an attorney for Mr. Fugazy, plans to
appeal the decision.
